r labor rights as well? Using a variety of archives and collected oral histories, Japanese American Incarceration uncovers the startling answers to these questions. Stephanie D. Hinnershitz's timely study connects the government's exploitation of imprisoned Japanese Americans to the history of prison labor in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aForced laborzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxForced removal and internment, 1942-1945. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campszUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConscript laborzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAsian American history.  aCoerced labor.  aInternment camps.  aJapanese American Resettlement.  aJapanese internment during WWII.  aLabor history.  aPoston Colony.  aPublic policy.  aWar Relocation Authority.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812299953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812299953/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK